{"id":"2209.02897","submitter":"Can Cui","authors":"Can Cui and Xue-Ning Bai","title":"Turbulence in outer protoplanetary disks: MRI or VSI?","comments":"9 pages, 10 figures, accepted for publication in MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stac2580","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The outer protoplanetary disks (PPDs) can be subject to the magnetorotational\ninstability (MRI) and the vertical shear instability (VSI). While both\nprocesses can drive turbulence in the disk, existing numerical simulations have\nstudied them separately. In this paper, we conduct global 3D non-ideal\nmagnetohydrodynamic (MHD) simulations for outer PPDs with ambipolar diffusion\nand instantaneous cooling, and hence conductive to both instabilities. Given\nthe range of ambipolar Els\\\"{a}sser numbers ($Am$) explored, it is found that\nthe VSI turbulence dominates over the MRI when ambipolar diffusion is strong\n($Am=0.1$); the VSI and MRI can co-exist for $Am=1$; and the VSI is overwhelmed\nby the MRI when ambipolar diffusion is weak ($Am=10$). Angular momentum\ntransport process is primarily driven by MHD winds, while viscous accretion due\nto MRI and/or VSI turbulence makes a moderate contribution in most cases.\nSpontaneous magnetic flux concentration and formation of annular substructures\nremain robust in strong ambipolar diffusion dominated disks ($Am\\leq1$) with\nthe presence of the VSI. Ambipolar diffusion is the major contributor to the\nmagnetic flux concentration phenomenon rather than advection.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Sep 2022 03:00:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 18 Sep 2022 04:58:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-21"}
